<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.voanews.com/article.cfm?objectID=FCE8E648-AD40-4804-AD35883E9B9B41F2&amp;title=Chinese%20Spacecraft%20Returns%20Safely%20to%20Earth&amp;catOID=45C9C78B-88AD-11D4-A57200A0CC5EE46C">Chinese Spacecraft Returns Safely to Earth.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
An unmanned Chinese spacecraft has returned safely to earth, bringing China one step closer toward a manned flight later this year. <br>
<br>
The state-owned Xinhua news agency reports the Shenzhou-Four landed safely Sunday night in the central region of Inner Mongolia, after orbiting the earth 108 times. <br>
<br>
Xinhua quotes officials as saying the successful launch and return of the craft shows China's technology for manned space flight is becoming more feasible. <br>
<br>
The spacecraft, which spent nearly a week in orbit, successfully performed several operations, including unfolding its solar panels. <br>
<br>
China's manned space program is a key project for the government. A successful manned flight would make China only the third country, after Russia and the United States, able to put a person in space on its own. <br>
<br>
